05534nam a22009015i 9780823289707DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232897077 a10.1515/97808232897072doi  a(DE-B1597)574294  a(OCoLC)1227393434  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBR1642.U5bO36 2021 7aREL1020002bisacsh04a322.4/409732231 aO'Donnell, S. Jonathon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPassing Orders :bDemonology and Sovereignty in American Spiritual Warfare /cS. Jonathon O'Donnell. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Paradise Has Walls -- t1 Nations Unto Light: Spiritual Warfare As Orthotaxic Religiosity -- t2 Jezebel Assemblages: Witchcraft , Queerness, Transnationality -- t3 The Islamic Antichrist: An Eschatology Of Blowback -- t4 Leviathan’S Wake: Demonology And The Passing Of Order -- tConclusion: Paradise Refused -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDemonization has increasingly become central to the global religious and political landscape. Passing Orders interrogates this centrality through an analysis of evangelical “spiritual warfare” demonologies in contemporary America. Situating spiritual warfare as part of broader frameworks of American exceptionalism, ethnonationalism, and empire management, author S. Jonathon O’Donnell exposes the theological foundations of the systems of queer- and transphobia, anti-blackness, Islamophobia, and settler colonialism that justify the dehumanizing practices of the current U.S. political order.O’Donnell argues that demonologies are not only tools of dehumanization but also ontological and biopolitical systems that create and maintain structures of sovereign power, or orthotaxies—models of the “right ordering” of space, time, and bodies that stratify humanity into hierarchies of being and nonbeing. Alternative orders are demonized as passing, framed as counterfeit, transgressive, and transient. Yet these orders refuse to simply pass on, instead giving strength to deviant desires that challenge the legitimacy of sovereign violence. Critically examining this challenge in the demonologies of three figures—Jezebel, the Islamic Antichrist, and Leviathan—Passing Orders re-imagines demons as a surprising source of political and social resistance, reflecting fragile and fractious communities bound by mutual passing and precarity into strategic coalitions of solidarity, subversion, and survival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aDemonologyzUnited States. 0aSpiritual warfarezUnited States. 0aWhite supremacy movementszUnited States. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aPolitical Science. 4aTheology. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh  aAmerican Politics.  aAntiblackness.  aDemonology.  aEvangelicalism.  aIslamophobia.  aOrthotaxy.  aQueer Dissidence.  aSettler Colonialism.  aSovereignty.  aSpiritual Warfare.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311072271040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823289707zCo-access DOI